04327nam a22006615i 9780814760079DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147600797 a10.18574/97808147600792doi  a(DE-B1597)547977  a(OCoLC)899211421  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD9940.A2bC94 2016 7aSOC0260002bisacsh04a746.920822231 aCzerniawski, Amanda M., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFashioning Fat :bInside Plus-Size Modeling /cAmanda M. Czerniawski. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4cÂ©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. From Books to Looks -- t2. How to Become a Plus-Size Model -- t3. Models of All (Plus) Sizes? -- t4. Disciplining Corpulence through Aesthetic Labor -- t5. Agents as Gatekeepers of Fashion -- t6. Selling the Fat Body -- t7. Stepping Out of the Plus-Size Looking Glass -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor two and a half years, Amanda Czerniawski was asociologist turned plus-size model. Journeying into a world where, as a size10, she was not considered an average body type, but rather, for the fashionindustry, "plus-sized," Czerniawski studied the standards of work and imageproduction in the plus-sized model industry.Fashioning Fat takes us through a model's day-to-day activities,first at open calls at modeling agencies and then through the fashion shows andphoto shoots. Czerniawski also interviewed 35 plus-size models about theirlives in the world of fashion, bringing to life the strange contradictions ofbeing an object of non-idealized beauty.Fashioning Fat showsus that the mission of many of these models is to challenge our standards ofbeauty that privilege the thin body; they show us that fat can be sexy. Many plus-sizemodels do often succeed in overcoming years of self-loathing and shame overtheir bodies, yet, as Czerniawski shows, these women are not the ones in chargeof beauty's construction or dissemination. At the corporate level, the fashionindustry perpetuates their objectification. Plus-size models must conform to animage created by fashion's tastemakers, as their bodies must fit withinnarrowly defined parameters of size and shape-an experience not too differentfrom that of straight-sized models. Ultimately, plus-size models find that theyare still molding their bodies to fit an image instead of molding an image ofbeauty to fit their bodies. A much-needed behind-the-scenes look at thisgrowing industry, Fashioning Fat is afascinating, unique, and important contribution to our understanding of beauty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aBody image. 0aPlus-size women's clothing industry. 0aSelf-esteem in women. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Sociology / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071187540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814760079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814760079.jpg  a978-3-11-071187-5  NYUP / FUP Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK